========================================

1. What is Vector?
------------------
- Dynamic array provided by STL.
- Stores elements in contiguous memory.
- Supports O(1) random access.
- Automatically manages memory.
- Can grow/shrink at runtime.

2. Internal Implementation
--------------------------
Vector maintains:
- Pointer to memory block
- Size (number of elements)
- Capacity (allocated memory)

When capacity becomes full:
1. Allocate larger memory block
2. Copy/Move existing elements
3. Free old memory
4. Update internal pointer

3. Size vs Capacity
-------------------
size()
------
- Number of elements currently stored in the vector.
- Increases/decreases as elements are added or removed.

capacity()
----------
- Total number of elements the vector can hold before reallocating memory.
- Usually >= size().
- Changes only when vector allocates more memory (or shrink_to_fit is used)

Key Points:
-----------
- size() <= capacity()
- size() changes when elements are added/removed.
- capacity() changes when vector reallocates memory.
- reserve() affects capacity, not size.
- resize() affects size (and may affect capacity).

size()     -> Number of elements stored.
capacity() -> Amount of allocated memory.

Example:
vector<int> v;

v.push_back(10);
v.push_back(20);

size() = 2
capacity() >= 2

