Interview Q:
When do vector iterators become invalid?
Q: When do vector iterators become invalid?

A vector iterator becomes invalid when an operation changes the
underlying memory location of the vector.

Most common reason:
- Reallocation due to push_back() when capacity is full.

Example:
---------

vector<int> v;

v.reserve(2);

v.push_back(10);
v.push_back(20);

auto it = v.begin();

cout << *it;   // 10

v.push_back(30);   // Capacity full -> Reallocation occurs

// it is now INVALID

cout << *it;   // Undefined Behavior

What happened internally?

Before push_back(30):

Memory A:
[10][20]

it --> 10

After push_back(30):

Memory B:
[10][20][30]

Old Memory A deleted.

Iterator still points to deleted memory.

Therefore:
it becomes invalid.
"If a vector reallocates its memory, all existing iterators, pointers, and references become invalid."

8. Complexity
-------------

Access using []          O(1)
Access using at()        O(1)
push_back()             Amortized O(1)
A single push_back() is not always O(1). When the vector runs out of capacity,
it performs a reallocation and copies/moves existing elements, making that
particular operation O(n). However, reallocations happen infrequently because
the capacity grows geometrically (typically doubles). Over many insertions,
the total cost is spread across all push_back() operations, so the average
cost per insertion is amortized O(1).

pop_back()              O(1)
insert at end           Amortized O(1)
insert in middle        O(n)
erase in middle         O(n)
find                    O(n)

